The paper deals with lower bounds for randomized communication complexity and query complexity, which are fundamental topics in theoretical computer science. The paper uses linear programming techniques to derive the partition bounds, which are shown to be stronger than other well-known bounds in both communication complexity and query complexity. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper involves information theory (cs.IT), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), and computational geometry (cs.CG) concepts, which are also relevant to the topic.
